“The management tried to create ‘fear’ among the Muslims that they would have to leave the country if the CAA and NRC [National Register of Citizens] are implemented,” Rakshala said in his complaint.

After the complaint, an image had gone viral, where three policemen, two of whom were in uniform and one in plain clothes, were seen questioning the students who were part of the play.

Fareeda Begum and Nazbunnisa were booked under Sections 504 (intentional insult with intent to provoke breach of peace), 505(2) (statements creating or promoting enmity, hatred or ill-will between classes), 124A (sedition), 153A (promoting, attempting to promote disharmony) and 34 (common intent) of the Indian Penal Code.

